---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Wage Theft Misconceptions | wagetheftcalc.com';
const description = 'Common myths and misconceptions about wage theft, FLSA rights, and recovering unpaid wages.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Wage Theft Misconceptions</h1>
  <h2>"I'm a salaried employee, so I don't get overtime."</h2>
  <p>Salary alone does not create an overtime exemption. You must also meet a duties test. Many salaried workers in non-managerial roles are misclassified as exempt and are owed overtime.</p>
  <h2>"My employer can deduct mistakes from my paycheck."</h2>
  <p>In most cases, no. Deductions for cash register shortages, broken equipment, or mistakes that bring wages below minimum wage violate the FLSA. State laws are often more restrictive.</p>
  <h2>"I signed a contract saying I'm an independent contractor."</h2>
  <p>Contract labels don't control worker classification. The FLSA uses an economic reality test. If your employer controls how, when, and where you work, you may be an employee regardless of what your contract says.</p>
  <h2>"Filing a claim will get me fired."</h2>
  <p>The FLSA prohibits retaliation for filing a wage complaint. If your employer retaliates, that is a separate violation with additional damages. Many workers successfully file claims and continue working.</p>
  <h2>"The amount is too small to bother."</h2>
  <p>Attorney fees are recoverable under the FLSA, meaning attorneys take these cases even for small individual claims. Collective actions allow similar employees to aggregate claims, making small-dollar violations economically viable to pursue.</p>
</BaseLayout>
